passages.text: Reiterate Rating: BUY | PO: 5.70 AUD | Price: 5.02 AUD

We expect Medibank's surprising pullback today (- 2.5%) to be short- lived and reiterate our Buy rating. We see a particularly attractive entry point into a high quality name. We lower our FY26 estimates on higher cyber costs (non- recurring) but lift outer year forecasts on a stronger- than- expected top- line and margin outlook for health insurance. We raise our PO to a Street- high of A\(5.70 (+6\%\) from A\)5.40) and reiterate our Buy with 17% total return potential. Shares trade at 19.5x FY27E earnings, offering 31- 32% ROEs (ex GW) over our forecast period and 7- 8% EPS/DPS CAGR.

We believe the market has under- estimated the trajectory of net margins for Medibank's health insurance business. This is due to three reasons: 1) we are still below pre- COVID margins in residents health insurance, 2) we expect faster- and more margin- accretive growth from the non- residents business, and 3) we expect MERs to continue to improve. We estimate Medibank's net margins can improve to 9.4% by FY28E (vs Cons at 9.0%). Our estimates are 1- 8% higher than Cons forecasts over FY26- 28E.

Market conditions are at a tipping point for Australian health insurers. We expect to see a pullback in marketing spend over FY26 as the industry seeks to rein in over- spending post COVID. Current industry MERs are 170bps higher than pre- COVID levels, and unsustainable in our view. Medibank is well positioned to benefit from disruption given its industry- leading expense ratio and continued discipline. We expect growth momentum from 2H to continue (BofAe 2.0% resident policyholder growth in FY26).

Medibank sees a strong M&A pipeline, which we estimate could deliver 3- 7% upside to FY27E earnings. Beyond M&A, the company has reiterated its capital management discipline which should be taken well and we see scope for additional capital return emerging from FY27.

Company DescriptionMedibank (MPL) is Australia's second- largest private health insurer with 24% market share. Its products are sold under its flagship Medibank brand and value- orientated AHM brand, offering hospital and extras/ancillary benefits cover for Australian residents. MPL also covers overseas students and workers. MPL offers complementary services through Medibank Health, supporting its health insurance customers through investments such at- home care, preventative care and telehealth services.

Investment RationaleWe have a Buy rating on MPL, which we see as a market- leading and high quality Australian health insurer. MPL offers exposure to structural growth in Australian private health insurance and attractive returns for shareholders as one of the most efficient operators. We see double- digit growth opportunities in Medibank Health with at attractive, at- scale margins. MPL deserves a valuation premium to the wider market given its strong market presence and highly defensive earnings stream.
1. Health insurance margins are set to expand further. We believe this has been underappreciated.

We believe the outlook for Medibank's health insurance operating margins remains very attractive, and potentially underappreciated by Consensus. We see a convincing path to an operating margin sustainably over \(9\%\) over the coming years (BofA 9.1- 9.4% over FY26- 28E) vs Cons expectations for no further progress from FY25 onwards (8.8- 9.0% over FY26- 28E).
Exhibit 1: We believe the gross and net margin outlook for the health insurance business has been underestimated Medibank Health Insurance gross and net (operating) margins, FY17-28E
Source: Company information, BofA Global Research estimates
We see three key reasons for this, which we discuss in greater detail below:

We see three key reasons for this, which we discuss in greater detail below:- We see further upside to the gross margin for residents health insurance,- We expect faster growth in higher- margin non- residents business, and- We expect the management expense ratio (MER) to continue to improve.

We do not have segmental splits between residential and non- residential business prior to FY20 (aka pre COVID), but the company's comments on the analyst call suggested its FY25 gross margin of \(16.2\%\) was still 20bps below its pre COVID levels.

This confirms that Medibank has not made excess profits at the expense of private hospitals during COVID, and that there is still further upside to the company's current resident health insurance gross margin. We conservatively expect the residents health insurance gross margin can recover (i.e., normalise) to \(16.4\%\) by FY28E though this could happen even faster.
Exhibit 2: We see further upside to resident health insurance gross margins, which we expect to normalise towards pre-COVID levels (16.4%) by FY28E
Source: Company information, BofA Global Research estimates

Medibank's non- residents gross margin is materially higher than its residents business (36.9% vs 16.2%), and also faster- growing. Medibank remains under- represented in this high- margin segment and will continue to focus on growth here over the coming years.

With student visa approval numbers up \(10\%\) Y/Y for FY26 (and a significant pipeline of student- to- worker visa conversions expected), we think this provides an attractive set- up for FY26 and beyond. We conservatively estimate non- resident gross profit CAGR of \(\sim 7\%\) over FY25- 28E vs resident gross profit CAGR of \(\sim 5\%\) . We expect the non- resident share of gross profit to increase from \(8.0\%\) in FY25 to \(8.4\%\) by FY28E.

Source: Company information, BofA Global Research estimates

Exhibit 4: Non-resident gross margins are significantly higher than resident margins, and should be accretive to overall gross margins Health Insurance gross margins (overall, residents and non-residents), FY20-28E
Source: Company information, BofA Global Research estimates

Medibank's philosophy has always been that MER improvements are for the benefit of shareholders. After a rare year of MER deterioration (from \(7.8\%\) to \(8.0\%\) ) driven by elevated investment spend and back- ended growth, Medibank has reiterated its expectation for MER to remain stable/improve over the coming years. We see no reason to question this outlook, particularly given the company's industry- leading expense ratio. We expect continued scale as Medibank pushes for market share gains and productivity savings through digitalisation and artificial intelligence are likely to drive further MER improvements.

Exhibit 5: Medibank has maintained its industry-leading expense efficiency (to the benefit of shareholders); we expect this leadership to continue Management expense ratios (MER) for Medibank, NIB and the industry, FY17-28E
Source: Company information, APRA, BofA Global Research estimates, Note: FY25 based on YTD performance for industry

As shown in Exhibit 5 above, the wider health insurance industry has an expense problem. This has been particularly true in recent years as excess COVID profitability across the industry has been reinvested in growth (higher marketing spend) to drive a higher MER. Based on FY26 YTD data from APRA (up to March 2025), the industry MER of \(10.6\%\) has already improved \(0.9\%\) pts vs FY25 but remains \(1.7\%\) pts higher than the pre- COVID average of \(- 8.9\%\) . We view this as unsustainable, and believe a tipping point is coming in FY26.

We reiterate our expectation for industry gross margin to normalise (lower) over FY26- 27E as approved price increases are likely to lag claims inflation: the average approved price rise of \(3.93\%\) from 1 April 2025 is tracking lower than current inflation trends at around \(4.5\%\) . Even Medibank's own price rise of \(3.99\%\) is tracking below its FY25 claims inflation ( \(2.2\%\) headline but \(4.5\%\) after adjusting for utilisation savings).

At an industry level, we see current MERs as unsustainable. We believe a tipping point is coming in FY26 as industry gross margins are set to normalise (lower). To avoid significant net margin compression, the industry will need to rein in costs. We believe we are starting to see the beginning of this, and competition
(marketing spend) is likely to reduce over the coming months. Medibank is well positioned to benefit from this.

We believe Medibank is already starting to see the benefits of reducing market competition, with an acceleration of growth across both resident brands (Medibank and ahm) in 2H. This corresponded with just a small increase in marketing spend in 2H (A\\$6m uplift). Total policyholder growth of \(1.0\%\) in 2H accelerated from \(0.4\%\) in 1H. We believe this momentum is set to continue into FY26 as competitors reign in marketing spend in order to control costs.

Medibank expects industry growth to moderate slightly in FY26 vs FY25 (- 2.3% system growth). We conservatively estimate Medibank can deliver \(2\%\) policyholder growth in FY26E, which allows for a much bigger slowdown in system growth (and also suggests upside risk for earnings).
Exhibit 6: Resident policyholder growth accelerated in 2H25; we expect this momentum to continue through FY26 Resident policyholder growth, FY23-28E
Source: Company information, BofA Global Research estimates
We see further upside risk to Medibank's already- attractive earnings outlook: BofAie 31- 32% ROEs ex goodwill and underlying EPS CAGR of \(7.5\%\) over FY25- 28E.

Medibank's A\\$150- 250m M&A budget (over FY24- 26) remains largely unutilised to date, with the company suggesting that only A\\$60- 70m had been spent so far. However at the same time, Medibank has announced it expects to invest towards the top end of this target range over the coming year. This is supported a "strong asset pipeline" and presents upside risk to our future earnings forecasts. We do not factor in any inorganic growth in our forecasts.

Simplistically, if Medibank were to invest at the top end of its A\\$150- 250m M&A budget, this would suggest a further A\\$180m of deployment. At a fairly low multiple of 10x earnings (10% return on invested capital), this would result in a c. A\\$18m uplift in post- tax earnings on an annualised basis. This equates to a \(- 3\%\) uplift to our FY27E forecasts. We see this as a floor in potential earnings uplift, particularly given that the group's ROE outlook is tracking at \(27 - 28\%\) over FY26- 28E. Applying a similar ROE assumption could equate to a \(7\%\) uplift to FY27E earnings.

Medibank's unallocated capital of A\\$251.9m at FY25 was meaningfully higher than expected, largely due to lower- than- expected growth in the company's other non- health insurance businesses. This capital is more than enough to support the group's near- term M&A ambitions (plans to invest at the top end of its A\\$150- 250m budget before the end of FY26). We also see scope to fund additional M&A beyond current guidance, which we conservatively estimate at A\\$100m per annum. Even after allowing for this, we still estimate unallocated excess capital of - A\\$300- 390m over FY27- 28E.

While Medibank's priority remains accretive M&A, the company has also indicated it would consider capital management actions if suitable opportunities did not eventuate in a reasonable timeframe. We do not expect this to be the case given the company's confidence in the near- term pipeline, but we think confirmation of disciplined capital management should be well received.
We see scope for excess capital return emerging in FY27 and beyond, particularly as we expect the group's unallocated capital position to continue to grow supported by strong earnings generation.

We also estimate A\\$180- 360m of additional unallocated capital from the potential release of APRA's A\\$250m supervisory charge, which could see the group lower its health insurance capital requirements back to 10- 12% (from 14% currently). We expect this could be returned to shareholders as a special dividend (A\\$6.5- 13.1c per share or 1.3- 2.6% of market cap). The timing and quantum of APRA's potential release of its supervisory charge remains uncertain, though Medibank has confirmed it is on track to move to its "embed" phase of its uplift program by the end of this calendar year, following its cyber incident in 2022.

This was perhaps the biggest disappointment of an otherwise strong update from Medibank. The company has guided for cyber crime costs to remain elevated in FY26 (A\\$35m vs A\\$40m in FY25). This was disappointing, given our previous expectation for costs to materially reduce from FY26 onwards.

The company expects to incur costs relating to the embedding of the IT security uplift program, but excludes the impacts from any potential findings or outcomes from regulatory investigations or litigation (which are likely to fall in FY27 costs). We expect costs to reduce in FY27 (BofAe A\\$15m).
While unhelpful headwinds near- term, we think it is important to remember that these costs are non- recurring in nature and do not affect our medium- or longer- term view of the company.

We update our Medibank estimates after a strong FY25 print and better- than- expected outlook for growth and margins. We lower our FY26 estimates by \(2\%\) on higher- than- expected near- term cyber crime costs, but this is non- recurring and we increase our FY27 estimates by \(2\%\)

We lift our PO by \(6\%\) to a Street- high of A\\$5.70 (from A\\$5.40) supported by increased outer year forecasts and Medibank's stronger- than- expected capitalisation. Our valuation methodology is unchanged.

We expect the surprising pullback in shares today (- 2.5%) to be short- lived and reiterate our Buy rating. We see an particularly attractive entry point into a high quality name. Shares trade at 19.5x FY27E earnings, at a deserved premium to the wider market given its highly defensive and conservative earnings profile. We estimate Medibank can deliver
7- 8% EPS/DPS CAGR over FY25- 28E, with earnings upside potential from M&A and upside to potential capital return.

Our MPL price objective of A\\$5.70 is based on an adjusted Gordon Growth Model. For the Health Insurance business, we use a discount rate of \(7.7\%\) and terminal growth rate of \(3.25\%\) which reflects the company's conservative reserving and consistent delivery of high quality earnings. For Medibank Health, we use a discount rate of \(8.7\%\) and growth rate of \(4.25\%\) reflecting a shorter track record and greater inherent earnings volatility beyond traditional health insurance but greater structural growth potential in preventative care and telehealth. We adjust for excess capital based on our view of minimum group capital requirements. We also adjust for debt (minimal for MPL) and non- controlling interests. At our PO, we estimate MPL shares would trade at 24.0x FY26E earnings.

Upside risks: 1) Higher average annual premium increases, 2) Better-than- expected expense ratio improvements, 3) Increasing private health insurance participation and system growth, 4) Supportive immigration policies, 5) Improving healthcare efficiency, 6) Supportive equity and credit markets.

Downside risks: 1) Lower average annual premium increases, 2) Worse- than- expected expense ratio improvements, 3) Decreasing private health insurance participation and system growth, 4) Restrictive immigration policies, 5) Government intervention for health insurers to subsidise private hospitals, 6) Slower- than- expected improvements in healthcare efficiency, 7) Significant volatility in equity and credit markets.
